info.title: VoiceBase v3 API
info.description:
The v3 documentation has been designed to allow you to follow-along in your preferred language by copying code examples on the right into your terminal (cURL) or your project code. We have also included a Postman collection you can execute from the Postman application or Chrome plugin directly. Some users find using the Postman collection an easy way to experiment with the API and modify the configuration values to suit their needs, but it is not required.

This documentation uses several default values for configuration and media which you may either modify in your code, or within Postman. These environemnt variables are: 
* bearer-token: 'YOUR-BEARER-TOKEN' should be replaced with your unique token.
* configuration: may be modified after you copy the code example and paste it in your project, or within the postman environment. 


# VoiceBase API Development with Postman

The "Run in Postman" button will download the entire collection of API endpoints to the Postman plugin or application on your computer and allow you to modify requests for experimentation

## Configuring your environment
The VoiceBase v3 Postman collection makes use of environment variables to customize the requests being sent. More information on managing Postman environments can be found at [Setting up an environment with variables](https://www.getpostman.com/docs/postman/environments_and_globals/manage_environments). 
Be sure to modify your environment with the correct values for 'bearer-token' and configuration.

post.description:
# Using local media
To upload a recording for transcription and analysis, attach the named media in the body of the request in the form field: media

# Using a remote media URL
VoiceBase can also fetch media from a remote URL using the mediaURL form field in the request body.

get.description:
# Example with Stereo
In this example, the agent spoke first, and said "Hello" and the caller spoke second and said "Hi".
Speaker identification is enabled by multi-channel audio, where each channel is associated with a specific speaker. For more information on how to use multi-speaker audio, see the [stereo](stereo.md) section.

# How to read it:
* "p" = Position (word # in the transcript)
* "c" = Confidence (A value between 0-1 that relates to the confidence percent ex: 0.88 = 88%.  When the metadata flag is present confidence contains an arbireary value.)
* "s" = Start time (milliseconds)
* "e" = End time (milliseconds)
* "w" = The word itself (When the metadata flag is present "w" refers to the speaker)
* "m" = metadata (In this case when "m": "turn" it is detecting a change in speaker)
